Lab 7 Machine Learning¶

Part A1¶

In this part, we explored on how to create a dataset that is modeled after the MNIST dataset. This involves handwriting the digits on paper, taking pictures of them, then performing image processing on each image to make it similar to the MNIST dataset. The goal is to use these images that we have created as test images for a logistic regression model that was trained with the MNIST dataset.¶

Below are the steps in processing the images taken as pictures from a phone to have properties similar to MNIST dataset:¶

The images are first prepared by handwriting a total of 60 drawings. The digits 0 to 9 were first drawn, five each. Then, A to J were drawn to be some symbols that are not 0-9 digits. Pictures of the drawings were taken and uploaded to the computer, which will then be processsed as below. The first step is to import the required libraries. The PIl library is used to load and save images and the skimage.orphology is used for the morphological filtering.¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
import os
from skimage.morphology import dilation, disk

Then, the image is loaded using Image.open() function from PIL. In the following, we are loading 2 images for comparison. The image is first loaded and converted to grayscale. It is loaded as an array, in which we then perform thresholding based on the pixel value. Since we wanted to have a light foreground (pixel value 255) and dark background (pixel value 0), so if the pixel value is smaller than the threshold (black handwritten drawing), then it will have pixel value of 255. The threshold of 80 is chosen after some experimentation to provide the best thresholded output. The two images after thresholding is displayed below.¶

Then, a bounding box is created around just the foreground or digit in the image. The list of x and y index that have values bigger than 0 are first extracted using np.where() function. The outputs are two lists containing index values. Then we found the max and min x and y array index and a new array is created based on those arrays, which would create a bounding array of the foreground. This array is then converted into an image using Image.fromarray() function. The results of the bounded digit in the images are as below.¶

Now that we have have the bounded image, it is time to downsize the bounded image to 20x20 using interpolation while keeping its aspect ratio. One of the reason to downsize is to have a consistent size across all images. The thumbnail() function is used to interpolate and downsize the image. The function is chosen because it allows resizing while keeping the aspect ratio. The bicubic interpolation is chosen because it will provide a good averaging, because it will average with 16 neighboring pixels. Since we are keeping the aspect ratio, it may be the case that either the height or width is not of length of 20 pixels. So, the way to fix this is to create a new image of size 20x20 using Image.new(), then pasting the current image in the middle of the 20x20 image using paste(). In order to perform this, the offset in both the x and y axis needs to be calculated by subtracting the width or height from 20, then divide it by 2 to get the distance from one side of it. Based on the offset, the image is pasted to the 20x20 image ant the result is as below. For visualization purposes, the image is enlarged again.¶

Next, the goal is to have the current 20x20 image to be translated to a 28x28 image and is centered based on the center of mass. This is to have the consistency across all images. In this step, the center of mass is calculated. The center of mass for x and y axis is calculated from the zeroth and first order moments. The COM of x is m10/m00 and y is m01/m00. m00 is the mass, so it is calculated by counting the nonzero pixels in the image. For the m01 and m10, they are calculated using the for loop, in which the values of the index for both axis is summed up when pixel is not 0. We have previously learned that the first order moments are the weighted sum of the pixels based on the distance of the pixel from the origin. The COM of x and y are then calculated. The program is as below.¶

In [153]:
# Find Center of Mass
m00 = np.count_nonzero(padded_image)
padded_image_array = np.array(padded_image)

m10 = 0 # x
m01 = 0 # y
for i in range(20):
    for j in range(20):
        if padded_image_array[i][j] > 0:
            m10 += j
            m01 += i

com_x, com_y = m10//m00, m01//m00

#===========================Second Example===========================

            m102 += j
            m012 += i

com_x2, com_y2 = m102//m002, m012//m002

Finally, it is time to paste the 20x20 image that we have to a 28x28 background image and translate it based on the COM value that we have calculated. A new background image of size 28x28 is created. Then, the 20x20 image is pasted on it, with translation of 13 subtracted by the COM on each axis. The digit 13 is the index 27 divided by 2, which results to 13.5, but with the decimal removed. Digit 27 is the maximum index. Now that we have the image array ready, it is converted to an image an is saved in .png format. It is saved to the idata folder directory, which will contain all of the images. The final two images of digit 3 and 7 are as shown below. For visualization purposes, the image is enlarged again.¶

The images processed using the step above are saved in the directory folder idata. Next, we would want to learn about the impact of the line thickness of the digits in the testing set. We created a similar testing set but with a different line thickness. Since the images in the testing set that are first created have thinner lines, a morphological filter was used to perform dilation. The dilation will expand the border or boundary of the foreground, which means that the lines will be thicker. With this dilation, we are hoping that it will become more similar to the MNIST data and to maybe get better prediction. In the experiment below, we will load two identical images, but will perform dilation on only one of them for comparison. The steps below are exactly the same to the previous experiment, but an extra step for dilation is added.¶

After clipping the foreground based on the bounding box, it is time to use the morphological filter to perform dilation. We are using the library scikit-Image, which is an image processing library. From the library, we have imported the dilation function and disk function. In performing morphological filtering like dilation, we would first need a structuring element. We have chosen to use a circle-shaped, so disk() function is used. After testing several radius sizes, we used radius = 7 as it gave the best line thickness to be compared to the MNIST. After the structure is created, the dilation is performed on the image array.¶

In [207]:
# Morphology using Dilation
selem = disk(7)
clipped_image2 = dilation(clipped_image, selem)

After the step above, we have the image array of the bounded image after dilation. The next few steps are similar to when dilation was not performed.¶

# Dilation step is added to the program

import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
import os
from skimage.morphology import dilation, disk

tempcount = 0
for filename in os.listdir(os.curdir):
    if filename.endswith(".jpg"):
        
        # Convert to binary image by converting to grayscale and threshold
        original_image = np.array(Image.open(filename).convert('L'))
        thresh = 80
        original_image_array = (original_image < thresh) * 255 # Inverse the value of 255 and 0

        # Bounding box
        x,y = np.where(original_image_array) # Get list of x and y values > 0
        x_max, x_min, y_max, y_min = x.max(), x.min(), y.max(), y.min()
        clipped_image = original_image_array[x_min:x_max,y_min:y_max]
        
        # Morphology using Dilation
        selem = disk(5)
        dilated = dilation(clipped_image, selem)

        # Resize along with aspect ratio and use bicubic interpolation to resize to 20x20
        clipped_image = Image.fromarray(np.uint8(dilated))
        im_thumbnail = clipped_image.thumbnail((20, 20),Image.BICUBIC)
        width, height= clipped_image.size[0], clipped_image.size[1]
        padded_image = Image.new("L", (20, 20))
        offset_x = (20 - width) // 2
        offset_y = (20 - height) // 2
        padded_image.paste(clipped_image, (offset_x, offset_y))


        # Find Center of Mass
        m00 = np.count_nonzero(padded_image)
        padded_image_array = np.array(padded_image)

        m10 = 0 # x
        m01 = 0 # y
        for i in range(20):
            for j in range(20):
                if padded_image_array[i][j] > 0:
                    m10 += j
                    m01 += i

        com_x, com_y = m10//m00, m01//m00

        # Translate to 28x28 image using Center of Mass
        final_image = Image.new("L", (28, 28))
        final_image.paste(padded_image, (13-com_y, 13-com_x)) # the middle is index 13.5
        name, ext = os.path.splitext(filename)
        path = os.path.join(os.getcwd(), "idata2/")
        Image.fromarray(np.uint8(final_image)).save(path + name + ".png")

# Read the NMIST dataset
memory = Memory(get_data_home())
@memory.cache()
def fetch_mnist():
    content = urlopen(
        'https://www.openml.org/data/download/52667/mnist_784.arff').read()
    data, meta = loadarff(io.StringIO(content.decode('utf8')))
    data = data.view([('pixels', '<f8', 784), ('class', '|S1')])
    return data['pixels'], data['class']
X, y = fetch_mnist()

In [142]:
""" Custom datatset loader
    based on https://github.com/utkuozbulak/pytorch-custom-dataset-examples
"""
import pandas as pd
import imageio

class SimpleDataset():
    def __init__(self, data_path, csv_name, transform = None ):
        """
        Args:
            data_path (string): path to the folder where images and csv files are located
            csv_name (string): name of the csv lablel file
            transform: pytorch transforms for transforms and tensor conversion
        """
        # Set path
        self.data_path = data_path
        # Read the csv file
        self.data_info = pd.read_csv(data_path + csv_name, header=None)
        # First column contains the image paths
        self.image_arr = np.asarray(self.data_info.iloc[:, 0])
        # Second column is the labels
        self.label_arr = np.asarray(self.data_info.loc[:, 1])
        # Calculate len
        self.data_len = len(self.data_info.index)
        
    def __getitem__(self, index):
        # Get image name from the pandas df
        single_image_name = self.image_arr[index]
        # Open image
        img_as_img = imageio.imread(self.data_path + single_image_name)
        
        # Get label(class) of the image based on the cropped pandas column
        single_image_label = self.label_arr[index]
        
        return (img_as_img, single_image_label)

    def __len__(self):
        return self.data_len

The list of images names, directories, and labels are listed in the labels.csv spreadsheet. The list is extracted using the SimpleDataset() function. Train logistic regression model with training set from MNIST¶

In this section, we are training our logistic regression model with the training set from our MNIST dataset. We first performed pre-processing using StandardScaler() function. What this does is to standardize our features in both training and testing set by removing the mean and scaling the standard deviation/variance. This allows our data to be centered around and have similar scale of variance. The mean and variance is chosen based in the training set and will be used in both train and test set. The training set is standardized so that none of the features can dominate the model, which causes other features to have no impact/contribution to the prediction. The testing set uses the same mean and variance because we would want all of the dataset to be shifted and scaled with the same number.¶

In [147]:
## for this demonstration each pixel scale is normalized 
## by the mean and standared deviation of the training set
## note the mean and stadard deviation are set by the
## training set only.

X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

## A more elegant preserntation for a confusion matrix
import itertools
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    #print(cm)

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.tight_layout()

K nearest neighbour¶

The first classifier that we are exploring is the K-nearest neigbor. The KNN is a type of non-parametric machine learning classifier that puts the training points in a feature space, then classifies the test data based on the closest neighbor(s) label. We experimented on how changing the values of nearest neighbors will impact the training and testing time and accuracy. The nearest neighbors values that we tested with are 1, 3, and 5. We are using a partial of the dataset to keep the test within 10 minutes.¶

We learned that for KNN, the train time is very quick because we only store the information on the training set. On the other hand, the testing time is much longer and depends on the size of the testing data, because we would need to compare the distance/difference of each point in the training and testing data ony-by-one. We have also learned that as we are comparing more near neighbors, the test time will increase as there are more points to compare with. However, the score/test accuracy will actually decrease when the number of neighbors increases. This is because of overfitting, in which the model no longer learns noise from the training set that will negatively impact the prediction of unseen testing data set. This usually happens when the model is too complex, such as when the number of near neighbours are too high. From the confusion matrix, we learned that most of the mistakes are in confusing between 4 and 9, and also 2 and 7. We will compare the confusion matrix with the other classifiers below.¶

Next, we explored on how Principal Component Analysis (PCA) can impact the training and testing time and accuracy. For 3 nearest neighbor, we experimented to train the model on just part of training set and also trying PCA. The first two models are on training and testing on one-third and one-fifth of the data. The last three models are on training with the data after performing PCA with n = 10, 20, and 40. The n input is the variable to choose how many principal components do we want to choose. The tradeoff is that more components will allow us to have higher variance, but it means that we will need more storage and more computation. As a result, the number of components chosen needs to be tweaked, to ideally be a low value that still has a high variance (>90%). We will analyze the difference in train and test time and accuracy.¶

With training and testing with just one-third and one-fifth of the data, we can see a pattern. When there is less training data, the train time will decrease and the score will also decrease. The score decreases because there are not enough training points that would provide a "complex-enough" model to predict the unseen testing data. We can also see how the test time significantly decreases when the testing data is smaller, as there are less number of points that requires distance comparison due to the nature of how KNN works.¶

Next, we have learned on how performing a PCA can help improve predictions. In general, PCA is a technique for dimensionality-reduction. We know that high-dimensionality will cause overfitting in our models and result in low test accuracy. Performing PCA allows us to decompose our data into a set of orthogonal components that will maximize the amount of variance. From the table above, we can see how performing PCA alows us to have lower training and testing time, and sometimes a higher accuracy. The n input parameter to PCA specifies the number of components to keep. When n=20, we can see that both the train and test time are significantly lower compared to when using part of the set. When compared to using 1/3 of the data set, we can see that the train and test time is only 10%, but it has a better test prediction. When we tried to increase n to 40, the model will become more complex. The train and test time slightly increases and the score increases too, resulting to the best prediction out of all the models. On the other hand, when n is decreased to 10, the model will just be too simple that test accuracy will be pretty low (0.924), despite the fact that the train and test time is very fast. Wrapping up, we can see how using PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the data really helps in having a quick training and testing. The resulting score will depend on the n parameter that is set, and a higher n may help to have a better performance compared to when not using PCA. Interestingly, looking at the confusion matrix for all 5 of them, they seemed to be pretty consistent with each other. A lot of 4s are predicted as 9s, and a lot of 8s are predicted as 3s.¶

Multi-layer perceptron¶

Next, we are exploring the multi-layer perceptron. The multi-layer perceptron is a class of neural network that is made up of multiple layers of perceptron. It will calculate the weights through the iterations of the feedforward and back propagations during the model's training. The multi-layer perceptron will be able to predict data that are not linearly separable due to having multiple-layers. We will be comparing on what will happen when different hidden layers are used. In this test, we are using 1 and 2 hidden layers. The entire data set is used as both the training and testing will be pretty quick. The max iteration is set as 100 to allow the weights to converge and make the best prediction.¶

The perceptron is a parametric model. We can easily identify that by how the train time is much longer than the test time (unlike a non-parametric model like KNN which has the reverse behavior). Train time is much longer because a the best weights would need to be found through iterations until it converges, while the testing step requires only calculations with the weights and figuring out the prediction from there. The train and test time of using 2 hidden layers took around 50% longer compared to using 1 hidden layer. Using 2 hidden layers also took more iterations: 64 vs 55. However, it is able to provide a better test prediction, although not by much (0.9731 vs 0.974).¶

Comparing the results in using MLP to KNN without PCA pre-processing, we can see that the test accuracy tends to be higher while the train and test time tends to be shorter. However, this is not a fair comparison because because KNN is using less data set to allow the experiment to be within 10 minutes. It may be the case that less training set would translate to less test accuracy, as a result this comparison will not be fair. One thing that we can tell is that multi-layer perceptron is faster then using KNN given that it is using the entire data set. Looking at the confusion matrix for both multi-layer perceptron, they are pretty consistent. It is interesting to see that the most error came from predicting 5 as 3, which is different to using the KNN model.¶

SVM¶

Finally, we experimented with Support Vector Machine. The SVM is a type of non-parametric classifier that maps the training set into a space and separate the different labels with a hyperplane that maximizes the distance between the two closest points. The SVM can use a kernel trick to classify a non-linearly separable data. We will be looking into the linear SVM that works only with linearly separable data and Radial Basis Functions SVM that will be able to classify non-linearly separable data. The RBF SVM have a gaussian function and has KNN-like properties. So, it is like a smoothed-version of KNN due to the gaussian function. We will compare the two SVM models' train and test time and their testing accuracy.¶

Looking at all of the tables that compares the train time, test time, and test accuracy of all of the models that we tested, we can learn on what are the good models that we can use for our application. One thing to note is that these models are tested on different data sizes, so the comparison is not entirely fair. However, we can see that using Multi-layer Perceptron would provide the highest test accuracy while the least train and test times. I will be going with a 2-hidden layer Multi-layer Perceptron if I am to choose a model for this application. Looking at the performance of K-Nearest Neighbor, it is also a pretty good classifier for this application. The test accuracy is very close to the test accuracy of using Multi-layer Perceptron, but the testing time is much higher, due to how KNN makes predictions. Out of all classifiers, the SVM seemed to be the poorest. Although linear SVM still has pretty good predictions of 0.926, the RBF SVM is really poor in making predictions for our application, despite an attempt with first performing PCA.¶
